{{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=2007 |Team=Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens |Image=YoUDee.jpg |ImageSize=140 x 140 |Conference=Colonial Athletic Association |Division= |ShortConference=CAA |Record=11â4 |ConfRecord=5â3 |TSNRank=2<ref name="Rank">{{cite news |title=University of Delaware Football A Consensus No. 2 Pick in Final NCAA Division FCS Top 25 Polls |url=http://www.bluehens.com/sportsinfo/football/fb07-finalpoll.html |work=University of Delaware |date=December 18, 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-19}}</ref> |FCSCoachRank=2<ref name="Rank"/> |HeadCoach=[[K.C. Keeler]] |HCYear= 6th |OffCoach=Kirk Ciarrocca |OCYear= |DefCoach=Nick Rapone |DCYear= |OScheme= |DScheme= |StadiumArena=[[Delaware Stadium]] |Champion=[[Lambert-Meadowlands Trophy#Lambert Cup|Lambert Cup]] winner |BowlTourney=[[NCAA Division I Football Championship]] vs. [[2007 Appalachian State Mountaineers football team|Appalachian State]] |BowlTourneyResult=L 49â21 }} The '''2007 Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football team''' represented the [[University of Delaware]] in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] [[Division I (NCAA)#Football Championship Subdivision|Football Championship Subdivision]] (FCS) college football in its [[2007 NCAA Division I FCS football season|seventh season]] as a member of the [[Colonial Athletic Association]] (CAA), and the football program's first season of play in the CAA.
[[K.C. Keeler]] served as head coach in his sixth season since replacing the legendary [[Tubby Raymond]]. Keeler previously brought the Blue Hens to the FCS championship game, winning it in 2003. In 2007, the team made it to the championship game again after posting an 11â3 record, but lost to the [[2007 Appalachian State Mountaineers football team|Appalachian State Mountaineers]], 49â21.
==Preseason== ===Conference changes=== The 2007 season marked the first season of play for the [[Colonial Athletic Association]], which was formed in 2005. From 1997â2006, the Delaware Blue Hens football team was a member of the [[Atlantic 10 Conference]]. Delaware, along with [[Hofstra University#Athletics and mascots|Hofstra University]], [[James Madison Dukes football|James Madison University]], the [[Maine Black Bears|University of Maine]], the [[UMass Minutemen football|University of Massachusetts]], the [[New Hampshire Wildcats|University of New Hampshire]], [[Northeastern Huskies|Northeastern University]], the [[Rhode Island Rams football|University of Rhode Island]], the [[Richmond Spiders football|University of Richmond]], [[Towson Tigers|Towson University]], [[Villanova Wildcats football|Villanova University]], and the [[William & Mary Tribe football|College of William & Mary]], left the Atlantic 10 Conference to form the twelve-team conference.<ref>{{cite news |title=UMass To Be A Part Of CAA Football Conference Beginning In 2007 |url=http://www.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stories/050405aai.html |work=[[CSTV]] |date=May 4, 2005 |accessdate=2010-11-19}}</ref>
