==Game notes== ===William & Mary=== {{see also|2007 William & Mary Tribe football team}} {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road='''Delaware''' |R1=0 ||R2=21 ||R3=7 ||R4=21 |Home=William & Mary |H1=3 ||H2=0 ||H3=7 ||H4=21 }}
In the first CAA Conference game of the newly-formed conference's history, Delaware senior running back [[Omar Cuff]] tied an NCAA record with seven touchdowns in the game. Cuff tied with [[Archie Amerson]] of [[Northern Arizona Lumberjacks football|Northern Arizona]], who set the record in 1996, and [[Jessie Burton (American football)|Jessie Burton]] of [[McNeese State Cowboys football|McNeese State]], who tied the record in 1998.<ref>{{cite news |title=Record Night for Cuff; Leads Delaware to 49 â 31 win over William & Mary |url=http://www.wboc.com/Global/story.asp?S=7009390 |work=wboc.com |date=August 30, 2007 |accessdate=2010-11-19}}</ref> Cuff rushed for 244&nbsp;yards and six touchdowns on 30 attempts, with four receptions for 52&nbsp;yards and a touchdown. Senior quarterback [[Joe Flacco]] passed for 202&nbsp;yards and one touchdown in the 49â31 victory over [[2007 William & Mary Tribe football team|William & Mary]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Delaware 49, William & Mary 31 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=272422729 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=August 30, 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref>
With the win, the Blue Hens became 1â0 on the season. {{clear}}
===West Chester===
{{Linescore Amfootball| |Road=West Chester |R1=0 ||R2=0 ||R3=7 ||R4=7 |Home='''Delaware''' |H1=21 ||H2=13 ||H3=7 ||H4=0 }}
In the first quarter of Delaware's home-opener against the [[West Chester Golden Rams football|West Chester Golden Rams]], quarterback Joe Flacco led the Blue Hens on a 62-yard drive that ended in a seven-yard touchdown run by Omar Cuff. On the Golden Rams' next drive, a tipped pass resulted in a Delaware interception. The Blue Hens took advantage of this opportunity, ending the drive with a one-yard touchdown run by Cuff. The Blue Hens led the [[West Chester Golden Rams football|West Chester Golden Rams]] 34â0 heading into halftime.<ref name="Roll">{{cite news |author=Frederick, Dave |title=Blue Hens roll to 41â14 victory over West Chester |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jfYkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KxIGAAAAIBAJ&pg=1091,7616436 |newspaper=[[Cape Gazette]] |date=September 13, 2007 |accessdate=2010-11-20}}</ref>
Cuff scored rushing four touchdowns in the first half, with 21 rushes for 93&nbsp;yards in the 41â14 win. Freshman running back Phillip Thaxton, who replaced Cuff in the second half, rushed for 177&nbsp;yards on 12 attempts. On his first collegiate carry, he scored a 62-yard touchdown. His 177&nbsp;yards was the most by a Blue Hen in his debut in college. Flacco finished with 305&nbsp;yards, with wide receiver Mark Duncan catching five passes for 121&nbsp;yards.<ref>{{cite web |title=West Chester 14, Delaware 41 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=272510048 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=September 8, 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref> Delaware finished with 599&nbsp;yards of total offense in their fourteenth-straight win over West Chester.<ref name="Roll"/>
With the win, the Blue Hens extended their record to 2â0. {{clear}}
===Rhode Island===
{{Linescore Amfootball| |Road=Rhode Island |R1=2 ||R2=0 ||R3=0 ||R4=7 |Home='''Delaware''' |H1=7 ||H2=14 ||H3=14 ||H4=3 }}
Joe Flacco passed for 337&nbsp;yards and three touchdowns on 25 completions. Junior wide receiver Aaron Love, playing through groin and shoulder injuries, caught 10 passes for 137&nbsp;yards and one touchdown. Mark Duncan caught six receptions for 109&nbsp;yards. Freshman cornerback Anthony Walters made five tackles and recovered a fumble in the endzone for a touchdown.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rhode Island 9, Delaware 38 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=272580048 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=September 15, 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref> {{clear}}
===Towson===
{{Linescore Amfootball| |Road='''Delaware''' |R1=7 ||R2=10 ||R3=7 ||R4=3 |Home=Towson |H1=0 ||H2=0 ||H3=7 ||H4=0 }}
The Delaware defense held Towson's offense to 157 total yards, with seven sacks on the quarterback. Sophomore defensive end Matt Marcorelle made six tackles with three sacks for 27&nbsp;yards. Omar Cuff rushed for 109&nbsp;yards and three touchdowns on 27 carries. Joe Flacco passed for 274&nbsp;yards and one interception. Aaron Love made seven receptions for 107&nbsp;yards.<ref>{{cite web |title=Delaware 27, Towson 7 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=272650119 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=September 22, 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref> {{clear}}
===Monmouth===
{{Linescore Amfootball| |Road=Monmouth |R1=7 ||R2=0 ||R3=0 ||R4=0 |Home='''Delaware''' |H1=21 ||H2=21 ||H3=0 ||H4=0 }}
Omar Cuff rushed for 73&nbsp;yards and two touchdowns on 16 carries, and caught a touchdown pass. He became the school's all-time scoring leader with 314 points, breaking the previous record of 308.<ref>{{cite news |title=Delaware Strikes Early as No. 12 Blue Hens Roll to 42â7 Victory Over Monmouth |url=http://www.bluehens.com/sportsinfo/football/fb07-monmouth.html |work=University of Delaware |date=September 29, 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-19}}</ref> Joe Flacco passed for 215&nbsp;yards and two touchdowns. Cornerback Fred Andrew returned an interception for a touchdown of 78&nbsp;yards. Phillip Thaxton rushed for a 14-yard touchdown, and tight end [[Robbie Agnone]] caught an 11-yard touchdown pass. Freshman safety Cody Cipalla made seven tackles (four solo).<ref>{{cite web |title=Monmouth 7, Delaware 42 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=272720048 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=September 29, 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref> {{clear}}
