===Villanova=== {{see also|Battle of the Blue}} {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road=Delaware |R1=3 ||R2=7 ||R3=0 ||R4=0 |Home='''Villanova''' |H1=0 ||H2=3 ||H3=0 ||H4=13 }}
Joe Flacco went 17-of-31 and passed for 145&nbsp;yards. Omar Cuff, playing through a back injury, rushed for 75&nbsp;yards on 17 attempts. Aaron Love made seven receptions for 79&nbsp;yards, and Anthony Walters made seven tackles.<ref>{{cite web |title=Delaware 10, Villanova 16 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=273210222 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=November 17, 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref> {{clear}}
===Delaware State=== {{see also|2007 Delaware State Hornets football team}} {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road=Delaware State |R1=0 ||R2=0 ||R3=0 ||R4=7 |Home='''Delaware''' |H1=20 ||H2=10 ||H3=14 ||H4=0 }}
Omar Cuff rushed for a school-record 288&nbsp;yards and four touchdowns on 38 carries. The previous record for rushing yards in a game was 272 by Daryl Brown in 1994. Cuff also broke the single-season rushing record with 1,657&nbsp;yards. The previous record was 1,625 by Germaine Bennett in 2003. Joe Flacco passed for 189&nbsp;yards and one touchdown on 11 completions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Delaware St 7, Delaware 44 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=273270048 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=November 23, 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref> {{clear}}
===Northern Iowa=== {{see also|2007 Northern Iowa Panthers football team}} {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road='''Delaware''' |R1=0 ||R2=19 ||R3=10 ||R4=10 |Home=Northern Iowa |H1=10 ||H2=3 ||H3=7 ||H4=7 }}
Erik Johnson recovered a fumble and returned it 55&nbsp;yards for a touchdown in the second quarter. Joe Flacco passed for 312&nbsp;yards and two touchdowns and scored a one-yard rushing touchdown in the fourth quarter. He broke the school record for passing yards in a season with 3,686. The previous record was 3,436 by [[Matt Nagy]] in 2000. Omar Cuff rushed for 102&nbsp;yards and one touchdown on 28 carries. Mark Duncan caught eight receptions for 112&nbsp;yards and one touchdown. Jon Striefsky missed two extra point attempts in the first half, but made two field goals distancing 47 and 42&nbsp;yards.<ref>{{cite web |title=Delaware 39, Northern Iowa 27 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=273352460 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=December 1, 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref> {{clear}}
===Southern Illinois===
{{Linescore Amfootball| |Road='''Delaware''' |R1=0 ||R2=7 ||R3=7 ||R4=6 |Home=Southern Illinois |H1=10 ||H2=0 ||H3=0 ||H4=7 }}
Joe Flacco went 21-of-38 and passed for 243&nbsp;yards and two touchdowns. Jon Striefsky kicked two field goals, breaking the school's and conference's single-season records for field goals with 21. Omar Cuff rushed for 102&nbsp;yards and caught four passes for 67&nbsp;yards.<ref>{{cite web |title=Delaware 20, S Illinois 17 |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=273420079 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=December 8, 2007 |accessdate=2010-07-20}}</ref> {{clear}}
===Appalachian State=== {{see also|2007 Appalachian State Mountaineers football team}} {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road=Delaware |R1=0 ||R2=7 ||R3=7 ||R4=7 |Home='''Appalachian State''' |H1=14 ||H2=14 ||H3=7 ||H4=14 }}
Joe Flacco passed for 336&nbsp;yards and one touchdown. Omar Cuff rushed for 83&nbsp;yards and one touchdown. The record attendance of 23,010 on hand at [[W. Max Finley Stadium|Finley Stadium]] was the largest neutral site crowd for the NCAA Division I Championship Game.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.goasu.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=104458&SPID=12811&DB_OEM_ID=21500&ATCLID=1545029 |title=Thrice is Nice: Apps Rout Delaware For Third-Straight National Title |work=Appalachian State University |date=December 14, 2007 |accessdate=2008-01-04}}</ref> {{clear}}
